 Format: You will use the following starter code to write the solution to the problem and enclose your code within delimiters.\n```python\nclass Solution:\n    def largestSubmatrix(self, matrix: List[List[int]]) -> int:\n        \n```\n\n### Answer: (use the provided format with backticks)\n", "response": "```python\nfrom typing import List\n\nclass Solution:\n    def largestSubmatrix(self, matrix: List[List[int]]) -> int:\n        if not matrix or not matrix[0]:\n            return 0\n        \n        m, n = len(matrix), len(matrix[0])\n        heights = [0] * n\n        max_area = 0\n        \n        for row in matrix:\n            # Update the heights array\n            for j in range(n):\n                heights[j] = heights[j] + 1 if row[j] == 1 else 0\n            \n            # Sort the heights array in descending order\n            sorted_heights = sorted(heights, reverse=True)\n            \n            # Calculate the maximum area with the current configuration\n            for i, height in enumerate(sorted_heights):\n                max_area = max(max_area, height * (i + 1))\n        \n        return max_area\n```\n\nThis solution calculates the largest submatrix of 1s after optimally rearranging the columns. It uses a heights array to keep track of consecutive 1s in each column, sorts this array in descending order for each row, and calculates the maximum possible area of a submatrix of 1s.", "estimated_date": 1610841600000}